Field Label:
Earlier I asked you about thoughts or ideas that come into your head over and over again. I would like to ask you more about (that/those) now. 


GENERAL PROBES-OBSESSIONS


Recurrent and persistent ideas, thoughts, impulses (initially experienced as intrusive and senseless).

Have you ever been bothered by thoughts in your head, that come over and over again and won't go away, or that didn't make sense?  (Like silly words or ideas about harming others/self, germs, illness, need to have things an exact way or anything else the child said)
Did you try to push the thoughts away?
Have you ever been bothered by pictures in your mind that kept coming back, such as pictures of violent things, like people being hurt?
Did you worry a lot about getting an illness or bad disease?
INTERVIEWER: If answers no to all,  SKIP to  Compulsion.
If yes: What kind of thoughts, images or impulses have you had? (Interviewer: Not simply excessive worries about real life problems.)

SPECIFIC THOUGHTS

I would like to ask you about some thoughts that people sometimes have. 
 
Have you had thoughts about:
Concern with harming others/self?
Pictures of violent things, like people being hurt?
A fear that you would do something or say something bad, even though you didn't want to (insults,  obscenities, stealing)?
Feelings that the bad things that happened were your fault?
Contamination/germs/illness?
Forbidden/bad thoughts?
Need for symmetry/exactness?
Religious obsessions?
Any other obsessions?
Specify (Other obsessions)

SYMPTOMS- OBSESSIONS


INTERVIEWER: Read grouped questions one at a time in a probing fashion then use responses to indicate the appropriate coded answer.

Attempts to suppress/neutralize
  Did you try not to think about [insert obsession here]? Or keep them out of your head? How? Did you try to think of something else, instead? Could you? Did you try to push the thoughts away? Where did you think the thoughts were coming from?

Person recognizes that the obsessions are the product of his/her own mind, not imposed from without
 Are these your own thoughts, or does someone else put them in your head?
Did having to think about [insert obsesssion here] seem silly? Did it make sense to you? Did you think you were thinking about [insert obsesssion here] too much?

Marked distress
 Did thoughts about [insert obsession here] upset you? Make you feel bad, nervous? A lot?
Did trying not to think about [insert obsession here] upset you a lot?

Time consumption

How much of the time did you have these thoughts about [insert obsession here]? Every day? Less? (If less, read responses)
Choices, Calculations, OR Slider Labels: 1, Less than once/week | 2, 1-2 times/week | 3, 3-5 times/week | 4, 6-7 times/week | 9, Unknown

Field Label: For how long? A few minutes? Longer?  How many times in a day? (RATE TOTAL TIME DURING A DAY, EVEN IF INTERMITTENT)
Choices, Calculations, OR Slider Labels: 1, Less than 1 hour/day | 2, 1-2 hours/day | 3, More than 2 hours/day | 9, Unknown

Field Label: INTERVIEWER:Does participant meet criteria for obsessions?

Some people feel like they have to repeat things over and over again to get rid of the thoughts in their head. Now I'm going to ask you some questions about this. 


GENERAL PROBES-COMPULSIONS


INTERVIEWER:Behavior is designed to neutralize/prevent discomfort or something dreaded from happening, but activity is either not appropriate or is excessive.
Have you ever saved up so many things that they got in the way? (Hoarding)
Have you ever had to do something over and over again that you couldn't keep yourself from doing?  Things like washing your hands over and over again, counting things, or having to check on things?
What about having to do something exactly the same way each time, and feeling you have to start over if you make a mistake?
What did you have to do?
INTERVIEWER: If no to BOTH Obsessions and Compulsions, END Obsession-Compulsion section.
